Redis pub/sub already handles the hard part -- any instance can publish and all instances receive. Here's the full scaling picture:

```
[Load Balancer (sticky sessions)]
      |         |         |
  [Node 1]  [Node 2]  [Node 3]
      \         |         /
       [Redis Pub/Sub Cluster]
                |
          [PostgreSQL]
```

Key considerations:

**Sticky sessions** -- WebSocket connections are long-lived, so the load balancer needs to route reconnections to the same instance (or handle the catch-up gracefully). Use IP hash or a connection-id cookie.

```nginx
# nginx.conf
upstream chat_servers {
  ip_hash;
  server node1:8080;
  server node2:8080;
  server node3:8080;
}

server {
  location /ws {
    proxy_pass http://chat_servers;
    proxy_http_version 1.1;
    proxy_set_header Upgrade $http_upgrade;
    proxy_set_header Connection "upgrade";
    proxy_read_timeout 3600s;
  }
}
```

**Presence tracking** -- Use Redis sets per room, but add instance-awareness:

```typescript
const INSTANCE_ID = uuid();

// Track which instance each user is connected to
await redisPub.hSet(`presence:${roomId}`, client.userId, INSTANCE_ID);

// On disconnect, only remove if still on this instance
async function handleDisconnect(client: Client) {
  for (const roomId of client.rooms) {
    const currentInstance = await redisPub.hGet(`presence:${roomId}`, client.userId);
    if (currentInstance === INSTANCE_ID) {
      await redisPub.hDel(`presence:${roomId}`, client.userId);
      await redisPub.publish(`chat:${roomId}`, JSON.stringify({
        type: 'user_left',
        userId: client.userId,
        roomId,
      }));
    }
  }
}
```

