You'll also want to handle the case where patterns should match directories, not just files. For example, `node_modules` should exclude the entire directory tree:
```rust pub fn should_exclude(&self, path: &Path) -> bool {
    let relative = path.strip_prefix(&self.root).unwrap_or(path);

    // Check each path component against patterns
    // so "node_modules" matches "node_modules/foo/bar.js"
    for ancestor in relative.ancestors() {
        if ancestor.as_os_str().is_empty() {
            continue;
        }
        let ancestor_str = ancestor.to_string_lossy();
        if self.patterns.iter().any(|p| p.matches(&ancestor_str)) {
            return true;
        }
    }

    let rel_str = relative.to_string_lossy();
    self.patterns.iter().any(|p| p.matches(&rel_str))
} ```

Here's a parser for the ignore file:
```rust use std::fs; use std::path::Path;
pub fn load_ignore_file(root: &Path) -> Vec<String> {
    let ignore_path = root.join(".filewatchignore");

    match fs::read_to_string(&ignore_path) {
        Ok(contents) => contents
            .lines()
            .map(|line| line.trim())
            .filter(|line| !line.is_empty() && !line.starts_with('#'))
            .map(String::from)
            .collect(),
        Err(_) => Vec::new(),
    }
} ```
Then merge them with CLI patterns:
```rust fn main() -> anyhow::Result<()> {
    let cli = Cli::parse();
    let root = Path::new(&cli.path).canonicalize()?;

    let mut patterns = cli.exclude.clone();
    patterns.extend(load_ignore_file(&root));

    let filter = ExcludeFilter::new(&root, &patterns)?;
    // ... rest of watcher setup
} ```
CLI flags take precedence by virtue of being checked first, and the ignore file patterns are appended. Since glob matching is order-independent (any match excludes), this is a clean merge.

